{\rtf1\ansi \deff0{\fonttbl{\f8\fswiss Arial;}}\margl1440\margr1440\pgnstart25\sectd\pgnrestart\pgnstarts25\footery1080{\header \pard\plain\qr MYARC ADVANCED BASIC\par }{\footer \pard\plain\qr     VERSION 4.0  DDI SOFTWARE  \chpgn \par }\pard\qj \plain\f8\fs20 CHARPAT\tab \tab \tab \tab \tab \tab \tab \tab \tab \tab       CHARPAT\par \par \par \par \par Format\par CALL CHARPAT(character-code,string-variable[,....])\par \par Cross Reference\par CHAR\par \par Description\par The CHARPAT subprogram enables you to ascertain the current character definition of specified characters.\par \par \tab Character-code is a numeric-expression with a value from 0 to 255, specifying the number of the character of which you want the current definition.\par \par \tab The pattern describing the character definition is returned in the specified string-variable. The pattern is in the form of a 16-digit hexadecimal code. See CHAR for an explanation of the pattern used for character definition.\par \par See Appendix B for a list of avilable characters.\par \par Example\par \par 100 CALL CHARPAT(33,C$)\par Sets C$ equal to "0010101010001000", the pattern identifier for character 33, the exclamation point.\par }
